      "rationale": "All three FEA solvers (FDA in-house code v4.2, Ansys Mechanical 2023 R1, DePuy Synthes internal solver v7.1) are operated under ISO 9001:2015-compliant quality management systems with documented software development lifecycle controls. Each solver has a current V&V plan, formal release qualification test suite with 100% pass rate, and version-controlled source or executable. Change control logs, regression test results, and configuration management records were reviewed and found complete. SQA level 5 is achieved: independent third-party audit of the SQA process was completed in 2025 with zero major non-conformances."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-code-verification-level5",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed using the Method of Manufactured Solutions (MMS) for all three solvers applied to representative nonlinear elasto-plastic beam-bending problems. Observed order of accuracy was confirmed to match theoretical order (2nd-order spatial, 1st-order temporal) within 2% for all QoIs. Round-robin benchmark comparisons against NAFEMS LE10 and NL1 benchmarks yielded errors < 0.15%. Full code verification reports with MMS source terms, error norms, and convergence tables are archived at the linked evidence nodes. Level 5 achieved: MMS applied, order-of-accuracy confirmed, cross-solver agreement demonstrated."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-discretization-level5",
      "rationale": "Systematic mesh convergence study conducted on three geometrically similar meshes (coarse: 18,400 elements; medium: 73,600 elements; fine: 294,400 elements) using second-order hexahedral and tetrahedral elements with contact zone refinement. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed per Roache (1998) for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm: GCI_fine < 0.8% for all QoIs, confirming solution is in the asymptotic convergence regime (apparent order p = 1.94–2.03). Production mesh is the fine mesh. Discretization uncertainty contribution to uval is 0.3–0.6% of QoI, negligible relative to experimental scatter. Level 5 achieved: GCI < 1%, asymptotic regime confirmed, three-mesh Richardson extrapolation documented."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-solver-error-level5",
      "rationale": "Iterative solver convergence verified at each load increment: force residual norm < 1×10⁻⁸ N and displacement residual norm < 1×10⁻¹⁰ mm for all increments. Newton-Raphson iteration converged in ≤ 6 iterations per increment throughout the nonlinear loading history. Time-step sensitivity study (halving the load increment) produced < 0.05% change in all QoIs. Contact constraint enforcement verified via zero-penetration checks at all slave nodes. Solver error contribution to combined uval is < 0.1%. Level 5 achieved: tight convergence tolerances documented, increment sensitivity confirmed, contact enforcement verified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-use-error-level5",
      "rationale": "Model setup and execution followed a formally documented Standard Operating Procedure (SOP-FEA-F1717-v3.2) with mandatory peer review at five checkpoints: geometry import, material assignment, boundary condition application, contact definition, and results extraction. Two independent analysts (senior and junior) executed the model in parallel; results were compared and discrepancies > 0.5% triggered mandatory review. All three solver teams completed the same SOP. Discrepancies between analysts were < 0.2% for all QoIs, confirming negligible use error. SOP and peer-review sign-off sheets are archived. Level 5 achieved: formal SOP, independent dual-analyst execution, documented peer review."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-model-form-level5",
      "rationale": "Model form selection is justified by a documented physics-basis assessment: (1) continuum solid mechanics with nonlinear kinematics (large-displacement, large-strain) is appropriate for the observed 40 mm displacement range; (2) isotropic hardening J2 plasticity with Voce hardening law is validated against Ti-6Al-4V coupon data (R²=0.998); (3) frictional contact (μ=0.2, Coulomb) between screw and rod is justified by tribological characterisation of the as-received interface. Alternative model forms considered and rejected: (a) linear elastic — insufficient for post-yield regime; (b) anisotropic plasticity — material texture not significant for wrought rod stock. Model-form uncertainty estimated at ±2.1% of yield force QoI via Bayesian model averaging across three solver implementations. Level 5 achieved: physics-basis documented, alternatives assessed, model-form uncertainty quantified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-model-inputs-level5",
      "rationale": "All model inputs are traceable to primary measurements from the same material lot and device batch used in validation testing. Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus: 114.2 ± 1.8 GPa (n=6 tensile coupons, ASTM E8). Yield strength: 924 ± 12 MPa. Voce hardening parameters fit from full stress-strain curves. Screw and rod geometry: CMM measurements on 5 representative parts, mean ± 1σ used as input distribution. Friction coefficient: pin-on-disc tribometry, μ = 0.20 ± 0.03. All input uncertainties propagated via Monte Carlo (50,000 samples, Latin hypercube sampling). Sobol total-order indices confirm Ti-6Al-4V yield strength (ST=0.63) and rod diameter tolerance (ST=0.22) as dominant contributors. Level 5 achieved: all inputs from primary measurements, full UQ propagation, sensitivity analysis documented."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-test-samples-level5",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested: 6 at Laboratory A (ISO/IEC 17025 accredited) and 5 at Laboratory B (ISO/IEC 17025 accredited). All constructs assembled from the same production lot (Lot 2023-NC-7.5-A) with dimensional inspection confirming all parts within drawing tolerances. Sample-to-sample dimensional variability characterised by CMM (n=11); CV < 1.2% for all critical dimensions. Construct assembly performed by trained technicians following ASTM F1717-21 Section 7. Traceability chain from raw material certificate to finished construct is complete and archived. Statistical power analysis (α=0.05, β=0.20, effect size δ=10%) confirms N=11 is adequate to detect a meaningful difference. Level 5 achieved: accredited labs, full lot traceability, dimensional characterisation, statistical power analysis."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-test-conditions-level5",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted strictly per ASTM F1717-21 at two independent accredited laboratories. Test frame calibration traceable to NIST standards (calibration certificates within 12-month validity). Crosshead displacement rate 5 mm/min ± 0.5%. Ambient temperature 23 ± 2°C, humidity 50 ± 10% RH, recorded throughout each test. Load cell uncertainty ± 0.5% of reading (k=2). Displacement transducer uncertainty ± 0.05 mm (k=2). Inter-laboratory reproducibility assessed via ANOVA: no statistically significant laboratory effect on any QoI (p > 0.15), confirming test condition equivalence across sites. All raw load-displacement data, machine logs, and calibration certificates archived. Level 5 achieved: two accredited labs, full environmental monitoring, NIST-traceable calibration, inter-laboratory equivalence demonstrated."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-input-equivalency-level5",
      "rationale": "A systematic input-equivalency matrix was constructed mapping each FEA model input to its experimental counterpart. Geometry inputs were set to CMM-measured means with tolerances propagated as described under Model Inputs. Material property inputs were set from coupon tests on the same lot. Boundary conditions (fixture stiffness, contact preload) were measured directly on the test machine and replicated in the FEA model. No surrogate or literature-derived values were used for any primary input. Residual discrepancies between model inputs and experimental conditions were quantified and included in the combined validation uncertainty uval. The input-equivalency report was independently reviewed by a third analyst. Level 5 achieved: full input-equivalency matrix, no surrogate inputs, independent review documented."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-e-uval-lt-1p96",
      "rationale": "Output comparison performed using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval for all three QoIs. Combined validation uncertainty uval computed as the root-sum-square of: experimental measurement uncertainty (u_exp), numerical solution uncertainty (u_num), and input parameter uncertainty propagated through the model (u_input). E/uval values: stiffness 0.031, yield force 0.412, force at 40 mm 0.887 — all well below the acceptance threshold of 1.96. Full-field load-displacement curve comparison also performed: FEA mean curve lies within the experimental 95% confidence band at all displacement increments from 0 to 40 mm. Graphical overlays and tabulated E/uval values are included in the archived validation report. Level 5 achieved: formal E/uval metric, full uncertainty budget, full-field curve comparison, all QoIs pass."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-qoi-relevance-level5",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly specified in ASTM F1717-21 as the required performance metrics for pedicle screw construct evaluation and are the same QoIs used in the FDA 510(k) submission pathway for this device class. A formal QoI relevance assessment was conducted linking each QoI to the clinical failure mode of concern (fatigue fracture of the rod or screw under cyclic spinal loading) via a documented failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA). Stiffness governs load sharing with the spine; yield force and force at 40 mm characterise structural reserve margin. No QoI was assessed that is not directly linked to a clinical or regulatory endpoint. Level 5 achieved: QoIs traceable to regulatory requirements and clinical FMEA, formal relevance assessment documented."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/morrison-cou2-validation-relevance-level5",
      "rationale": "A formal validation relevance assessment was conducted using the ASME V&V 40 validation pyramid framework. The validation activity (ASTM F1717 bench test) is at the system level, directly replicating the regulatory submission test. The COU is prediction of F1717 performance of the same device family. Similarity between validation conditions and COU conditions was assessed across six dimensions: (1) geometry — identical device, same nominal dimensions; (2) material — same lot, same processing route; (3) loading — identical ASTM F1717-21 protocol; (4) boundary conditions — same fixture design; (5) environment — same ambient conditions; (6) scale — full-scale construct. All six dimensions rated as high similarity. No extrapolation beyond the validated domain is claimed. The COU is bounded within the validated operating space. Level 5 achieved: six-dimension similarity assessment, no extrapolation claimed, validation at system level matching COU level."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/morrison-cou2-mrl5-accepted-20260419",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team lead",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The Morrison COU2 non-cannulated F1717 compression-bending FEA model is accepted as credible for its intended use at Model Risk Level 5. The basis for acceptance is as follows: (1) All 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors have been assessed and all achieve the required level of 5, with no factor below required level. (2) The validation metric E/uval is 0.031, 0.412, and 0.887 for construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement respectively — all well below the pre-specified acceptance threshold of 1.96. (3) The percentage difference between FEA predictions and experimental means is 0.5%, 2.0%, and 1.9% for the three QoIs respectively, all within the <10% acceptance criterion. (4) Full uncertainty quantification via Monte Carlo propagation (50,000 samples) and Sobol sensitivity analysis has been completed; dominant uncertainty sources are identified and characterised from primary measurements. (5) The validation activities are directly relevant to the COU: same device, same protocol, same QoIs, no extrapolation. (6) Inter-laboratory reproducibility has been confirmed (p > 0.15 for all QoIs), strengthening confidence in the experimental reference data. (7) Software quality assurance, code verification, and discretization error controls are all at the highest rigor level. No weakeners were identified during the structured evidence review. The credibility assessment team unanimously recommends acceptance of this model for use in the regulatory submission supporting the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw 510(k).",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
